{"updated_at": {"date": {"d": "28", "m": "06", "Y": "2026"}, "time": {"H": "20", "M": "50", "S": "02"}}, "news": [{"title": "Salman Khan family\u2019s sea-facing Bandra residential project gets MCZMA\u2019s clearance", "para": "Salman Khan's mother, Salma Khan, has received a crucial clearance from the Maharashtra Coastal Zone Management Authority for a new sea-facing residential building in Bandra. The project, a ground-plus-six-storey structure, will be built on a plot previously owned by Mary Clotilda Baptista. The MCZMA emphasized adherence to existing land use and FSI norms from January 18, 2019, for the redevelopment.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/residential/salman-khans-family-secures-mczma-approval-for-luxe-sea-facing-bandra-project/132056278?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-19968/132056278.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "residential"}, {"title": "Prestige Group holds \u20b965,000 crore unrecognised revenue in books on record pre-sales: Chairman", "para": "Prestige Estates Projects holds a substantial Rs 65,000 crore in unrecognised revenue, fueled by robust housing sales. The company achieved record bookings of Rs 30,024 crore in FY26 and anticipates even stronger performance this fiscal year, targeting Rs 35,000-36,000 crore in sales.  Discussions are underway to adopt a more immediate revenue recognition method.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/prestige-group-reports-65000-crore-in-unrecognised-revenue-amid-record-sales-growth/132055560?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-340196/132055560.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "industry"}, {"title": "Chandigarh allows bed & breakfasts in residential areas", "para": "Chandigarh's residential sectors are set for a transformation as the administration permits Bed & Breakfast (BnB) operations in large homes.  Eligible houses, at least 500 square yards, can now host tourists under a new tourism department policy. This move, however, faces strong opposition from residents concerned about commercialization, increased traffic, and noise.  Officials aim to boost tourism and homeowner income, learning from a previous failed 2008 scheme.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/hospitality/chandigarh-introduces-bed-breakfasts-in-residential-areas-despite-concerns/132056140?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-1381580/132056140.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "hospitality"}]}